            "text": " In the above four examples (unit cube, octahedron  $O_n$ , cylinders, half-balls), we used Proposition 1 (or Proposition 2) to argue that  $b_2(K) > 1$ . For these examples, the fact that  $b_2(K) > 1$  was already known: the cylinder, like the cube, is decomposable, the half-ball has (many) points of positive curvature on its boundary, and it was directly shown in [\\[SZ15\\]](#page-9-1) that  $b_2(O_n) = 2$  (by taking well-chosen segments). The half-ball example suggests that  $\\max_{F} \\frac{\\text{Isop}(F)}{\\text{Isop}(K)}$  could be minimal when K is in its John's position.",
